NE/J013595/1</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>659E7D95-DAA8-4E8E-8214-B93922D269A6</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:policyInfluenceOutput><gtr:areas/><gtr:description>Data cited in IPCC AR5</gtr:description><gtr:geographicReach>Multiple continents/international</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>EA9F4402-41B5-43BD-AB09-0B82942A8513</gtr:id><gtr:type>Citation in other policy documents</gtr:type></gtr:policyInfluenceOutput></gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:researchMaterialOutput><gtr:description>A technological development is developed through which the stable carbon-, oxygen- and non-exchangeable hydrogen-isotopic ratios (d13C, d18O, d2H) are determined on a single carbohydrate (cellulose) sample with precision equivalent to conventional techniques. This triple-isotope approach offers significant new research opportunities, most notably in physiology and medicine, isotope biogeochemistry, forensic science and palaeoclimatology, when isotopic analysis of a common sample is desirable or when sample material is limited</gtr:description><gtr:id>097F9263-4FE4-4A92-B79C-CDB18AAD8966</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The development of a triple-isotope method represents a significant improvement over existing methods. The system performs comparably with standard methods in terms of analytical precision and importantly, requires less than a third of the sample material needed for single determinations using standard techniques. Analysis time is comparable with that of a single isotope determination by continuous flow. As the samples do not require nitration prior to analysis, significant efficiencies arise in the development of multiple-isotope time series. A further benefit of running three isotopic measurements on a single common sample is the increased statistical confidence in the mean value resulting from replicate analyses in cases where sample material is limited. If the triple-isotope approach is routinely adopted, we anticipate that the added information provided by the hydrogen-isotope data from a-cellulose samples will greatly facilitate modelling of hydrogen-isotope fractionation in plants and lead to a more complete understanding of carbon-, oxygen- and hydrogen-isotopic variability in the Earth system</gtr:impact><gtr:providedToOthers>true</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>Simultaneous determination of COH stable isotopes in organic matter</gtr:title><gtr:type>Technology assay or reagent</gtr:type><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2014</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:researchMaterialOutput></gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/A30251B0-A13F-4943-9536-7C70A8CB5F7B"><gtr:id>A30251B0-A13F-4943-9536-7C70A8CB5F7B</gtr:id><gtr:title>Simultaneous determination of stable carbon, oxygen, and hydrogen isotopes in cellulose.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Analytical chemistry</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/3cfc6a6df0295b3919759b87a835fdf4"><gtr:id>3cfc6a6df0295b3919759b87a835fdf4</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Loader NJ</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2015-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0003-2700</gtr:issn></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/80CC5195-5389-483B-9D94-73AD85FA144F"><gtr:id>80CC5195-5389-483B-9D94-73AD85FA144F</gtr:id><gtr:title>High-precision ultra-distal Holocene tephrochronology in North America</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Quaternary Science Reviews</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/db060c5b347e291d84714badc29dd79c"><gtr:id>db060c5b347e291d84714badc29dd79c</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Pyne-O'Donnell S</gtr:otherNames></gtr:auth